      <div set:html={`<h2 id="amazon-drm-free-epub-downloads-2026">Amazon DRM-Free EPUB Downloads 2026: How to Download Kindle Books as EPUB</h2>

<p>In early 2026, Amazon quietly rolled out one of the most reader-friendly policy changes in Kindle's history: authors and publishers can now opt in to sell DRM-free EPUB versions of their books on the Kindle Store. When they do, you can download an actual <code>.epub</code> file from your Amazon library — no conversion required, no Calibre plugins, no DRM stripping.</p>

<p>This guide shows you exactly how to check if a Kindle book you own is eligible, where to download the EPUB file, what you can do with it once you have it, and what limitations to expect.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="what-changed-in-2026">What Changed in 2026</h2>

<p>Historically, Amazon offered two types of DRM on Kindle books: <strong>DRM-enabled</strong> (the default for nearly all titles) and <strong>DRM-free</strong> (at the author's discretion). Before 2026, even DRM-free books could only be downloaded as MOBI or AZW3 files from Amazon's content library. EPUB was never an option.</p>

<p>That changed in January 2026 when Amazon introduced the ability for KDP authors to offer DRM-free EPUB downloads directly. When an author opts in, readers see a new "Download available in additional formats" badge on the Kindle product page, and the EPUB file becomes available in their Amazon Content and Devices library.</p>

<p>This is <strong>not</strong> the same as Amazon's "Send to Kindle" conversion pipeline (which accepts EPUB files and converts them to KFX on the backend). This is a native EPUB download — the file you get is the actual EPUB the author uploaded, without any format transformation or DRM encryption.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="how-to-check-if-a-kindle-book-is-drm-free">How to Check if a Kindle Book Is DRM-Free</h2>

<p>Not every Kindle book qualifies. DRM-free EPUB availability depends entirely on the publisher's choice. Here is how to check:</p>

<h3>Before you buy: Look for the badge</h3>
<p>On any Kindle book's product page on Amazon, look for one of two badges near the price or format information:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>"Download available in additional formats"</strong> — the publisher has opted into DRM-free EPUB download. This is what you want.</li>
  <li><strong>"Simultaneous Device Usage: Unlimited"</strong> — another signal that the book is DRM-free. It means Amazon doesn't limit how many devices can hold the book simultaneously, which is only possible without DRM.</li>
</ul>
<p>If neither badge is present, the book is almost certainly DRM-protected. You'll still be able to read it on Kindle devices and apps, but you cannot download a DRM-free EPUB copy.</p>

<h3>For books you already own: Check your content library</h3>
<p>If you already purchased a book and want to know whether a DRM-free EPUB is available:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Go to <strong>Amazon.com &gt; Account &gt; Manage Your Content and Devices</strong></li>
  <li>Click the <strong>Content</strong> tab (this is your book library)</li>
  <li>Find the book in your list and click the <strong>Actions</strong> button (labeled with three dots or an arrow)</li>
  <li>Look for <strong>"Download"</strong> in the dropdown menu</li>
  <li>If the download menu shows both <strong>"EPUB"</strong> and <strong>"Kindle Format"</strong> options, the book is DRM-free</li>
</ol>

<hr />

<h2 id="how-to-download-epub-from-amazon">How to Download the EPUB File</h2>

<p>Once you have confirmed a book is DRM-free, downloading the EPUB takes about 30 seconds:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Go to <strong>Amazon.com &gt; Account &gt; Manage Your Content and Devices</strong></li>
  <li>Click the <strong>Content</strong> tab</li>
  <li>Find the book and click <strong>Actions &gt; Download</strong></li>
  <li>Choose <strong>"EPUB"</strong> from the format dropdown (the other option is "Kindle Format" which downloads AZW3)</li>
  <li>The file downloads as <code>Title.epub</code> — typically a few MB for a standard novel</li>
</ol>

<p>The downloaded EPUB is a standard, validated EPUB 3 file. You can open it immediately in any EPUB reader — Calibre, Apple Books, Kobo, Google Play Books, or any app that supports the format.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="what-happens-to-your-kindle-copy">What Happens to Your Kindle Copy</h2>

<p>Downloading the DRM-free EPUB does <strong>not</strong> affect your Kindle library copy. The book remains in your Amazon account, accessible via Send to Kindle or device sync. You now simply have two copies: the Kindle-encrypted one in your Amazon library and a DRM-free EPUB on your local machine.</p>

<p>This is important: Amazon's DRM-free EPUB is an <strong>additional</strong> download, not a replacement. It coexists with your existing Kindle license. You can delete the local EPUB and re-download it later from your content library whenever you want.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="which-authors-are-opting-in">Which Authors Are Opting In?</h2>

<p>As of mid-2026, the adoption is growing but not universal. Based on the titles currently showing the DRM-free badge:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Independent and self-published authors</strong> — Many indie authors on KDP have opted in, especially those who also sell directly through their own websites or other platforms (Gumroad, Leanpub, Payhip). For them, DRM-free EPUB is a distribution-neutral format that works everywhere.</li>
  <li><strong>Technical and reference publishers</strong> — O'Reilly, Manning, and Pragmatic Bookshelf titles on Kindle have a high opt-in rate. These publishers have long sold DRM-free through their own channels, so Amazon's EPUB option is a welcome addition.</li>
  <li><strong>Small-to-medium press</strong> — Mixed adoption. Some mid-size publishers see DRM-free EPUB as a competitive advantage against larger houses; others are still evaluating.</li>
  <li><strong>The Big Five publishers</strong> — Generally not opting in as of June 2026. Penguin Random House, Hachette, HarperCollins, Simon &amp; Schuster, and Macmillan continue to use Kindle's standard DRM. This is expected to be a multi-year transition, if it happens at all.</li>
</ul>

<p>To find DRM-free Kindle books, search for the phrase <strong>"Download available in additional formats"</strong> on Amazon — the search results page will surface eligible titles.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="what-you-can-do-with-a-drm-free-epub">What You Can Do With a DRM-Free EPUB</h2>

<p>Once you have the EPUB file, it's truly yours. Here are the things you can do that a DRM-protected Kindle book wouldn't allow:</p>

